  "prompt": "What is the difference between active voice and passive voice?",
  "response": "The difference between active voice and passive voice lies in the way the subject and the object of a sentence are presented, as well as the focus and clarity of the sentence.\n\n### Active Voice:\nIn the **active voice**, the **subject** of the sentence performs the action. The subject is the doer of the action, and the sentence is direct and concise. It typically follows this structure:  \n**Subject + Verb + Object**\n\n**Example:**  \n\"The dog chased the ball.\"  \n- Subject: The dog  \n- Verb: chased  \n- Object: the ball  \n\nIn this sentence, the dog (the subject) is performing the action of chasing the ball (the object).\n\n### Passive Voice:\nIn the **passive voice**, the **subject** of the sentence is the receiver of the action. The focus is on what is being done to the subject, rather than who is doing it. It typically follows this structure:  \n**Object + Verb (with \"to be\") + (by + Subject)**\n\n**Example:**  \n\"The ball was chased by the dog.\"  \n- Object: The ball  \n- Verb: was chased  \n- Subject: the dog  \n\nIn this sentence, the ball (the object) is receiving the action, and the dog (the subject) is mentioned at the end.\n\n### Key Differences:\n1. **Focus:**  \n   - Active voice emphasizes the doer of the action.  \n   - Passive voice emphasizes the receiver of the action.  \n\n2. **Clarity:**  \n   - Active voice is usually clearer and more direct.  \n   - Passive voice can be more indirect and can obscure the doer of the action.  \n\n3. **Use of \"to be\":**  \n   - Passive voice always uses a form of \"to be\" (e.g., is, are, was, were) followed by the past participle of the verb.  \n\n### When to Use Each:\n- **Active voice** is generally preferred in most writing because it is concise and engaging.  \n- **Passive voice** is useful when the doer of the action is unknown, unimportant, or intentionally hidden, or when the focus is on the action or the recipient.  \n\n**Example of Passive Use:**  \n\"Mistakes were made.\"  \nHere, the focus is on the mistakes, not on who made them.  \n\nBy understanding these differences, you can choose the voice that best suits your writing purpose.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
